%T A395523 4,2,2,2,2,4,4,2,4,4,4,2,2,2,2,20,2,2,2,2,4,2,2,2,2,4,4,4,2,2,4,4,2,2,
%U A395523 2,4,4,2,2,2,20,2,4,2,2,4,2,4,2,2,4,4,2,4,4,4
%N A395523 a(n) is the period of {F^(i) mod n} (a sequence of functions Z -> Z/kZ), where F^(i) means the i-th iteration of the Fibonacci sequence (A000045).
%C A395523 In other words, a(n) is the smallest p such that F^(i)(m) == F^(i+p)(m) (mod n) for all m and all sufficiently large i.
%C A395523 a(n) divides a(A001175(n)). Conjecture: a(n) = a(A001175(n)) for all n != 2 or 4.
%H A395523 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395523/a395523.txt">PARI Program</a>
%e A395523 a(7) = 2 because:
%e A395523  - {F^(2)(m) mod 7} is of period 24: {0, 1, 1, 1, 2, 5, 0, 2, 5, 1, 6, 6, 0, 6, 6, 1, 5, 2, 0, 5, 2, 1, 1, 1};
%e A395523  - {F^(3)(m) mod 7} is of period 24: {0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 5, 5, 6, 1, 6, 2, 2, 0, 2, 2, 6, 1, 6, 5, 5, 1, 1, 1, 1};
%e A395523  - for every even i >= 4, {F^(i)(m) mod 7} is of period 24: {0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 5, 1, 2, 1, 2, 6, 6, 0, 6, 6, 2, 1, 2, 1, 5, 1, 1, 1, 1};
%e A395523  - for every odd i >= 5, {F^(i)(m) mod 7} is of period 24: {0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 5, 1, 6, 1, 6, 2, 2, 0, 2, 2, 6, 1, 6, 1, 5, 1, 1, 1, 1}.
%e A395523 In conclusion, {F^(i) mod 7}, as a sequence of functions Z -> Z/7Z, has period 2.
